<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>

<chapter xml:id="ch-quadratic-expressions-and-equations" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Quadratic Expressions and Equations</title>

  <introduction>
    <definition xml:id="def-quadratic-expression">
      <statement>
        <p>
       A <term>quadratic expression</term> is a mathematical phrase where the highest power of the variable (usually <m>x</m>) is <m>2</m>. 
       It represents a value that changes depending on what <m>x</m> is, but it does not include an equality sign.
    </p>
    <p>
        The general form of a quadrqatic expression is:
    </p>
    <p>
        <m>ax^2 + bx + c</m>
    </p>
    <p>
        where:
    </p>
    <p>
      <m>a</m>, <m>b</m>, and <m>c</m> are constants (numbers).
    </p>
    <p>
        <m>x</m> is the variable.
    </p>
    <p>
       <m>a</m> cannot be zero, if it were, the <m>x^2</m> term would disappear, and the expression would just be a linear expression.
    </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>
    <definition xml:id="def-quadratic-equation">
      <statement>
         <p>
        A <term>quadratic equation</term>, on the other hand, is a mathematical statement that asserts that a quadratic expression is equal to something (often <m>0</m>). 
        It represents a relationship between the variable and the constants, and it can be solved to find the values of <m>x</m> that make the equation true.
    </p>
    <p>
      The standard form of a quadratic equation is:
    </p>
    <p>
      <m>ax^2 + bx + c = 0</m>
    </p>
    <p>
      where <m>a</m>, <m>b</m>, and <m>c</m> are constants, and <m>a \neq 0</m>.
    </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>
  </introduction>
